     &lt;div class=&quot;summary&quot;&gt;
      {$entry-&gt;summary}
      &lt;a href=&quot;{$entry-&gt;link}&quot; class=&quot;more&quot; aria-label=&quot;Read more: {$entry-&gt;title|cms_escape:htmlall}&quot;&gt;{$readmore}&lt;/a&gt;
     &lt;/div&gt;
    {else if $entry-&gt;content}
     &lt;div class=&quot;content&quot;&gt;
      {$entry-&gt;content}
     &lt;/div&gt;
    {/if}
    {if !empty($entry-&gt;extra)}
     &lt;div class=&quot;extra&quot;&gt;
      {$entry-&gt;extra}
     &lt;/div&gt;
    {/if}
    &lt;div&gt;
  &lt;/article&gt;
{/foreach}{* items *}
&lt;!-- End News Summary Template --&gt;

property.content:
&lt;p&gt;This fully functional installation of CMS Made Simple is ready to be built into anything you can imagine.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you are new to CMS Made Simple, the best place to start is with the &lt;a title=&quot;CMS Made Simple documentation site&quot; href=&quot;http://docs.cmsmadesimple.org/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;documentation&lt;/a&gt;. If you&apos;re ready to get your hands dirty, log in to the site admin console &lt;a title=&quot;CMSMS Demo Admin Panel&quot; href=&quot;admin&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt; (or if this is not your site, go to &lt;span style=&quot;white-space: nowrap;&quot;&gt;yoursite.com/[path]/admin&lt;/span&gt;). Explore the templates provided. They are sprinkled with comments and tips for modifying or building your own designs.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you need further help, various support options are described &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.cmsmadesimple.org/support/options/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;License&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The license which applies to CMS Made Simple is the &lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; title=&quot;General Public License&quot; href=&quot;http://www.gnu.org/licenses/licenses.html#GPL&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;GPL&lt;/a&gt; version 3 (or later) from the Free Software Foundation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Some independently-developed add-on modules may have a different (compatible) license.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The CMS Made Simple community is at your service if you need help with your site. Here is where you find more information and support:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://docs.cmsmadesimple.org/&quot;&gt;the official documentation&lt;/a&gt; -- Start there, the documentation is maintained by the CMSMS developers.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://forum.cmsmadesimple.org/&quot;&gt;the Forum&lt;/a&gt; -- There you can search for answers to your questions or ask just about anything.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://www.cmsmadesimple.org/support/documentation/chat&quot;&gt;Slack&lt;/a&gt; -- Many CMSMS developers hang out there, along with other people who are ready to discuss and give support.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;http://www.cmsmadesimple.org/support/options&quot;&gt;Other&lt;/a&gt; -- Check there to get advice about paid support which might be available.
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please remember that the people involved in developing and supporting CMSMS have day jobs and other duties and will not be available 24/7. Be patient and polite and you will get better answers.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you want to contribute to the development of CMSMS itself, you are very welcome to do so. You can contact us on &lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://www.cmsmadesimple.org/support/documentation/chat&quot;&gt;Slack&lt;/a&gt; or hit the &lt;a class=&quot;external&quot; href=&quot;https://forum.cmsmadesimple.org/&quot;&gt;forums&lt;/a&gt; to get involved.
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Is &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CMS_Made_Simple&quot;&gt;this&lt;/a&gt; a reliable source of information?
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;CMS Made Simple&amp;trade; was first released in July 2004 as an open source (&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-2.0.html&quot;&gt;GPL&lt;/a&gt;) package, which it remains to this day.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Since 2004, the core system has been regularly improved and updated with features, security releases, code improvements and much more. In that time, many new versions have been released, each an improvement on the previous. In the summer of 2015, version 2.0 was released. It was a nearly-complete overhaul of the system. As we noticed our user base maturing to more advanced developers creating sites and applications, and larger design firms producing hundreds of CMSMS projects, it helped steer the project towards the powerful application base it is today.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s not just our own user base that has given us such great support. CMS Made Simple has garnered a number of awards since its creation including runner up (twice) and winner of Pact Publishing&amp;rsquo;s &amp;lsquo;Best Overall Open Source Content Management System&amp;rsquo; in their annual Open Source Awards.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;The Development Team&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;CMSMS is developed by an international team of professionals who volunteer their time and effort to design, develop, maintain, and market the system. In many cases this is in addition to running busy web and software development businesses themselves. Over past years, many outstanding individuals have contributed their time and helped to shape the system that you can download today. You can find out more about the current developers &lt;a title=&quot;CMSMS Dev Team&quot; href=&quot;https://www.cmsmadesimple.org/about/team/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;, as well as what they can offer through their own professional services.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Development Team meets officially once a month, but remains in contact daily, collaborating within a defined organisational structure.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
The Dev Team is always delighted to hear from people who feel they have the resources and time to get involved. If you think you may be such a person, click &lt;a title=&quot;Join the CMSMS Dev Team&quot; href=&quot;https://www.cmsmadesimple.org/community/get-involved/develop/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt; to find out more.
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;CMS Made Simple is an open source Content Management System. It&amp;rsquo;s built using PHP and the&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;Smarty&quot; href=&quot;http://www.smarty.net/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Smarty&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;template engine, which keep content, functionality, and display separate.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;FOR EDITORS&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;At its most simple level, CMSMS is a system to help you keep a website updated through a comprehensive&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;Content Manager&quot; href=&quot;https://docs.cmsmadesimple.org/content-2/content-manager&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Content Manager&lt;/a&gt;, which allows both editing and creation of new pages in real time, and a News module which allows the creation and control of article-based content such as news or blog posts. Supported by a&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;File Manager&quot; href=&quot;https://docs.cmsmadesimple.org/content-2/file-manager&quot;&gt;File Manager&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;for uploads and images, a&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;Search Module&quot; href=&quot;https://docs.cmsmadesimple.org/tags/search&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;frontend&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;Admin Search&quot; href=&quot;https://docs.cmsmadesimple.org/tags/admin-search&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;backend&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;Search Module, and a permissions-based&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;Backend Users&quot; href=&quot;https://docs.cmsmadesimple.org/user-management/backend-users&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Backend Users&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;manager, CMSMS is extremely easy to use, making it a delight for non-technical content editors to manage the day-to-day running of a site.&lt;br /&gt;[&lt;a title=&quot;For Editors&quot; href=&quot;https://www.cmsmadesimple.org/why-cmsms/for-designers&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;More&lt;/a&gt;]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;FOR DESIGNERS&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Beyond content management, CMSMS is actually a powerful and customisable system that makes the perfect core for markedly more advanced sites and applications. For designers, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;Smarty&quot; href=&quot;http://www.smarty.net/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Smarty&lt;/a&gt;-based templating engine means that there are virtually no restrictions on how the site can look. Unlike many other systems on the market, you will not be forced to shoehorn your design ideas into a pre-purchased template structure. Although there are commercial and free&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;CMSMS Themes Site&quot; href=&quot;https://themes.cmsmadesimple.org/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;themes&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;available, templating is so simple (with no need to know PHP!) that most designers find themselves adapting an existing design&amp;mdash;or building a new one from scratch&amp;mdash;in no time. The system lends itself to responsive design, and works extremely well with responsive frameworks such as&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;Get Bootstrap&quot; href=&quot;http://getbootstrap.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Twitter Bootstrap&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;Zurb Foundation&quot; href=&quot;http://foundation.zurb.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Zurb Foundation&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;[&lt;a title=&quot;For Designers&quot; href=&quot;https://www.cmsmadesimple.org/why-cmsms/for-designers&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;More&lt;/a&gt;]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;FOR DEVELOPERS&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;CMS Made Simple&apos;s core provides for powerful expansion through the use of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;Smarty&quot; href=&quot;http://www.smarty.net/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Smarty&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;templating engine, a robust module&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;CMSMS API&quot; href=&quot;http://www.cmsmadesimple.org/APIDOC2_0/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;API&lt;/a&gt;, and the ability to include your own PHP functions via&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;User Defined Tags&quot; href=&quot;https://docs.cmsmadesimple.org/tags/user-defined-tags&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;User Defined Tags&lt;/a&gt;. Combined, these provide the ability to make sites into powerful applications while keeping the content and design separate. You can choose between file or database templates (including template inheritance), complete control over caching, and a granular permissions system.&lt;br /&gt;[&lt;a title=&quot;For Developers&quot; href=&quot;https://www.cmsmadesimple.org/why-cmsms/for-developers&quot;&gt;More&lt;/a&gt;]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;FOR EVERYONE&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In addition to the above sections there is a vast array of powerful&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;CMSMS Modules&quot; href=&quot;http://dev.cmsmadesimple.org/project/list/module&quot;&gt;modules&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;created by the extended CMSMS community, many of which can be installed and ready to use at the click of a button within the&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;Module Manager&quot; href=&quot;https://docs.cmsmadesimple.org/modules/core/module-manager&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Module Manager&lt;/a&gt;. Adding a suite of modules, combining them with templates and core or user defined tags, rapidly allows for the creation of sites and applications with complex functionality without ever losing the simplicity of use for the website editor.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You can find out more about why CMSMS is ideal for your project&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;{cms_selflink href=&apos;why-use-cms-made-simple&apos;}&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;CMSMS is a fast and efficient system for creating stunning and sophisticated websites.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;ADDING SITE CONTENT IS JUST A FEW CLICKS AWAY&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Content Manager makes content management simple. That&apos;s sort of our thing! Reorder site pages via drag and drop, and edit their contents with a click. All with no knowledge of HTML. Let the designers worry about the look, while the editors focus on content. Editing content is done with a simple editor with all the tools you&apos;ll recognize from word processors.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;ANY DESIGN YOU CAN IMAGINE&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Join the growing number of design professionals who have discovered the foolproof elegance of CMS Made Simple.&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A question we often get asked is &quot;where are the templates?&quot; Although themes available, CMSMS was designed to eliminate the need to restrict yourself to premade or purchased templates. With some HTML and CSS knowledge, a developer can use Design Manager to put together a completely custom design in short order. With the inclusion of a responsive framework, it&apos;s even faster. Still want to use an existing design? No problem, CMSMS makes it easy to add your existing code: insert a few Smarty tags in key places, and you&apos;re off to the races. If you need a bit of help getting started, review the theme used for this page, or one of the themes available on the &lt;a href=&quot;https://themes.cmsmadesimple.org&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;CMSMS Themes&lt;/a&gt; site.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;EDIT SITE LAYOUT ON THE FLY&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Using file or database templates, and a bit of &lt;a title=&quot;Smarty&quot; href=&quot;http://www.smarty.net/&quot;&gt;Smarty&lt;/a&gt; knowledge, developers have full control over layouts. Responsive sites, especially with frameworks, are simple (there it is again) to test and maintain.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;EXTENDING A WEBSITE HAS NEVER BEEN MORE SIMPLE&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;With a wide range of core and independently-developed&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;CMSMS Forge&quot; href=&quot;http://dev.cmsmadesimple.org/project/list/module&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;modules&lt;/a&gt;, a fully documented&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;CMSMS API&quot; href=&quot;http://www.cmsmadesimple.org/APIDOC2_0/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;API&lt;/a&gt;, the ability to include PHP code via&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;CMSMS Documentation Site - UDTs&quot; href=&quot;https://docs.cmsmadesimple.org/tags/user-defined-tags&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;User Defined Tags&lt;/a&gt;, and full&amp;nbsp;&lt;a title=&quot;Smarty&quot; href=&quot;http://www.smarty.net/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Smarty&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;template inheritance, there&apos;s no limit to the complexity you can include in the website. CMSMS is fully extensible, and is a perfect base for your applications.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Using the Navigator module you can easily split site navigation in two parts. On this page the top level in the pages hierarchy is displayed horizontally, and depending on what page is displayed, a localized sub-menu is displayed vertically to the left. In this case the sub-menu to the left displays the sub-levels (children) to &lt;strong&gt;TODO PAGE TITLE&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;The {ldelim}Navigator{rdelim} tag&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
A &lt;code&gt;{ldelim}Navigator{rdelim}&lt;/code&gt; tag is inserted twice in the page template. First where the main navigation is, which should only show the top level. It looks like this: &lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;{ldelim}Navigator template=&apos;Simple Navigation&apos; number_of_levels=&apos;1&apos;{rdelim}&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The sub navigation should only contain the second level and down, depending on what is selected on the first level. Also, the third level links should only display when its parent on the second level is clicked, otherwise they are hidden. That is, the second level is collapsed unless the current page has sub pages.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The tag for the sub navigation looks like this: &lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;{ldelim}Navigator template=&apos;simple_navigation.tpl&apos; start_level=&apos;2&apos; collapse=&apos;1&apos;{rdelim}&lt;/code&gt;/&lt;pre&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Style sheets for the menu&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As the main navigation and the sub navigation need to be styled differently (one horizontal, the other vertical), two navigation style sheets are applied to this page. &lt;strong&gt;Navigation Simple - Horizontal&lt;/strong&gt; is for styling the horizontal main menu. &lt;strong&gt;Navigation Simple - Vertical&lt;/strong&gt; contains the styles for the sub navigation to the left.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Both using the same Navigator template&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, as you could see, both parts of the navigation are using the same navigation template. That is because the output code is the same. It is only through CSS that the two parts get styled differently.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Moving the sidebar to the right&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You can easily relocate the sidebar with the sub navigation to the right instead. Look in the &lt;strong&gt;Layout Top menu + 2 columns&lt;/strong&gt; style sheet for the &lt;code&gt;flex:TODO;&lt;/code&gt; property in the &lt;code&gt;div#sidebar&lt;/code&gt; element. Change that to &lt;code&gt;flex:TODO;&lt;/code&gt; and the sidebar with the menu will instead be on the right side of the content. Of course you will also have to adjust the margins for the sidebar and the div#main, basically just swap the left and right margins.&lt;/p&gt;

tag.code:
$thisYear=date(&apos;Y&apos;);
if(!empty($params[&apos;start&apos;]) &amp;&amp; is_numeric($params[&apos;start&apos;]) &amp;&amp; $params[&apos;start&apos;] &gt;= 2004 &amp;&amp; $params[&apos;start&apos;] &lt;= $thisYear){
 $startCopyRight=$params[&apos;start&apos;];
}else{
 $startCopyRight=&apos;2004&apos;;
}
// check if start year is this year
if($thisYear == $startCopyRight){
// it was, just print this year
 return $startCopyRight;
}else{
// it wasn&apos;t, print start year and this year separated by a dash
 return $startCopyRight.&apos;-&apos;.$thisYear;
}
